\f1\b\fs32 \cf0 Some thoughts on writing and editing 
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li1417\sl233

\f0\fs20 \cf0 <link>http://michaelcumming.com/2009/10/some-thoughts-on-writing-and-editing/</link> <pubDate>Wed, 07 Oct 2009 16:18:47 +0000</pubDate> <dc:creator>michael</dc:creator> <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.michaelcumming.com/?p=240</guid> <description></description> <content:encoded><![CDATA[Writing can be an overwhelming experience, especially for those with \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl233\sa230
\cf0 attentional deficit issues. Here are some tricks I have learned to help reduce my cognitive overload when writing and editing: \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl233
\cf0 <p> &nbsp; </p> <h3><strong>Express yourself first, edit later</strong></h3> <ul> \
\pard\pardeftab720\li710\sl231
\cf0 <li>Don't expect the first expression of an idea to be elegant, well-formed, or to make any sense</li> <li>Through skillful editing, silk purses can be made from sow's ears</li> <li>The writing/editing process is highly iterative; don't be surprised if it takes time</li> \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl233
\cf0 </ul> <h3>Writing as a tool for thinking</h3> <ul> \
\pard\pardeftab720\li710\sl231
\cf0 <li>As you write you might start to think about things in a new way</li> <li>It may be difficult to predict where a document might lead before you actually write it</li> <li>This emergent aspect is what makes writing exciting</li> \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl233
\cf0 </ul> <h3>Mechanical editing</h3> <ul> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi710\ri0\sl233
\cf0 <li>A large part of editing is mechanical or technical and thus could, in theory, be automated (that is, any monkey could be trained to do it)</li> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi710\sl231
\cf0 <li>Such editing need not be too difficult conceptually</li> </ul> <h3>Good content requires more than technique</h3> <ul> \
<li>Even with perfect technical editing, there is no guarantee that the content of writing will have any value</li> </ul> <h3>Number of words</h3> <ul> \
<li>If you can express the same thought in fewer words, then use fewer words</li> \
<li>However, don't be too miserly with words; excessive density or compactness of writing should be avoided</li> </ul> <h3>Contiguity of similar ideas</h3> <ul> \
\pard\pardeftab720\li710\sl231
\cf0 <li>Put ideas that are similar, next to one another, using cut and paste</li> <li>If there is repetition, then get rid of something</li> <li>Don't say the same thing in different parts of the same document, except occasionally for rhetorical effect</li> \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl233
\cf0 </ul> <h3>Order and flow</h3> <ul> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi710\sl231
\cf0 <li>Often, sufficient ideas are present in a document but are not in the proper order</li> \
<li>Put ideas in the proper order so that they flow well and unfold elegantly</li> </ul> <h3>Conclusions</h3> <ul> \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl233\qj
\cf0 <li>If you make a conclusion using words such as 'therefore' or 'so', you should support your conclusion with a progression of plausible assertions</li> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi710\sl231
\cf0 <li>Don't assume, as a given, what you are tying to prove</li> \
<li>Sometimes lines of reasoning lead to crazy conclusions; sometimes such conclusions turn out to be true</li> </ul> <h3>Avoid conclusions if necessary</h3> <ul> \
<li>Often the available evidence is too sketchy or ambiguous to make firm conclusions</li> \
<li>Asking the right questions might be a worthwhile contribution</li> </ul> <h3>Back to front structure</h3> <ul> \
<li>If you come to an interesting conclusion at the end of a document, it might be a good idea to put that idea at the beginning so people have some idea where you are headed</li> </ul> <h3>Hidden assumptions</h3> <ul> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi710\ri0\sl231
\cf0 <li>Hidden assumptions are things assumed to be true without their existence being acknowledged and with no evidence of their truthfulness provided</li> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi710\sl231
\cf0 <li>Try to identity and examine hidden assumptions; this can often be an interesting and fruitful enquiry</li> </ul> <h3>Knowledge as 'frozen ignorance'</h3> <ul> \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl233
\cf0 <li>Often things that 'everyone knows' turn out not to be true</li> <li>Assume that your ignorance of the world is much greater than your knowledge</li> </ul>]]></content:encoded> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi1417\ri0\sl231
\cf0 <excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[Writing can be an overwhelming experience, especially for those with attentional deficit issues. Here are some tricks I have learned to help reduce my cognitive overload when writing and editing.]]></excerpt:encoded> \
