\f1\b\fs32 \cf0 Portion size: American vs Dutch 
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\li1417

\f0\fs20 \cf0 <link>http://michaelcumming.com/2011/07/portion-size-american-vs-dutch/</link> \
<pubDate>Fri, 29 Jul 2011 16:20:13 +0000</pubDate> \
<dc:creator>michael</dc:creator> \
<guid isPermaLink="false">http://michaelcumming.com/?p=1504</guid> \
\pard\pardeftab720\li1417\sl233
\cf0 <description></description> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi1417\ri0\sl231\sa230
\cf0 <content:encoded><![CDATA[<a href="http://michaelcumming.com/2011/07/portion-size-american-vsdutch/buffet/" rel="attachment wp-att-1523"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1523" title="Buffet" src="http://michaelcumming.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/buffet.jpg" alt="Buffet" width="259" height="194" /></a> \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl233\sa230
\cf0 A recent trip to Pittsburgh illustrated something striking about the eating habits of two countries we\'92ve lived in: USA and the Netherlands. \
In the USA the pattern for food portion size is \'91more is more.\'92 In the Netherlands it is \'91less is more.\'92As someone who watches his weight, I have come to appreciate the Dutch approach. \
In America, portion size is a market-driven phenomenon. There the market dictates that people should be presented with more food than they will ever need. Food in low-end restaurants -- which we tend to frequent -- is glossy, high in saturated fats and involves comically high calorie counts. We all know where this leads, and it isn\'92t pretty. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl233\sa230
\cf0 But as a tourist, this can be an attractive and entertaining proposal. \'93Let\'92s take another trip to the buffet, we\'92re on vacation!\'94 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl231\sa230
\cf0 This is fun in the short-term but it does encourage obesity. It is a lead anchor wrapped around the ankle of the American public. It is death by a thousand cookies. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl233\sa230
\cf0 Clearly, open buffets are more a threat to the survival of the USA than are jihadists. \'93We have found the enemy and it is us.\'94 \
The Netherlands, in contrast, is a deeply Calvinist country where food is looked on a necessity for sustaining life rather than a cheap entertainment, or something that will being pleasure. You eat to live, you don\'92t live to eat. New visitors are sometimes taken aback by this, trained as they are to view the Dutch purely through the prism of soft drugs and prostitution. \
I have been through many a Dutch office luncheon, which typical involves rolls with a single slice of cheese. They carefully count out the quantities required so if there are ten attendees there are exactly ten rolls. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl231\sa230
\cf0 When you first encounter this behavior you are taken aback, trained as we are to see an affluent society as one in which there is always more than enough to eat. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl233\sa230
\cf0 When the Dutch see food consumption become a pleasure they call this \'91Burgundian.\'92 This suggests a more Catholic, free and easy approach to food, as found in countries to the south such as Belgium and France. These countries are known for the quality of their food as well as a complete lack of Protestant guilt in consuming it. \
However, as a way to run a country there is much to be said about limiting caloric intake and fostering guilt in consuming more than you need. It lengthens lives and increases the quality of life. This is why the Dutch are so tall and slender. They save money, look great, all the time honouring their forebears who survived hard times with a few potatoes and a stinky herring, eaten from a wooden bowl. \
One thing about fatness is that the rich tend to be less fat than the poor. This is especially true in the USA. As Duchess of Windsor said: \'93You can never be too rich or too thin.\'94 In Pittsburgh, obesity appears to be a problem. In Manhattan, much less so. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl233\sa230
\cf0 By this logic, the Dutch take the path of the trophy wife or the socialite, while many Americans the path of those less interested in the social value of their appearance -- they depress their \'91market value\'92 by their discretionary, dietary behaviors. This is somewhat puzzling in a highly competitive, market-driven economy. In Europe it seems there is a socially acceptable \'91floor\'92 beneath which most prefer not to tread. \
Of course you can have both a highly developed \'91Burgundian\'92 approach to food, as well as a tendency not to become huge. This is what you find in many countries, such as France, Belgium or Japan. These places seem like the best of both worlds. Obesity there is less of an issue, while excellent restaurants attract both fat and thin. \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl233
\cf0 This is probably why so many Dutch vacation in the south of France.]]></content:encoded> \
