\cf0 <description></description> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi1417\ri0\sl231\sa230
\cf0 <content:encoded><![CDATA[[caption id="attachment_1646" align="alignnone" width="300" caption="Ben at the bell console, St Paul&#39;s Presbyterian Church, Hamilton, ON"]<a href="http://michaelcumming.com/2012/05/playing-the-bells-at-st-pauls-hamilton/_1070998-rw2/" rel="attachment wp-att1646"><img class="size-medium wp-image-1646" title="_1070998.RW2" src="http://michaelcumming.com/wpcontent/uploads/2012/05/1070998.RW2_-300x200.jpg" alt="Ben at the bell console, St Paul's Presbyterian Church, Hamilton, ON" width="300" height="200" /></a>[/caption] \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl233\sa230
\cf0 This weekend, the boys and I visited <a href="http://stpaulshamilton.ca/" target="_blank">St Paul\'92s Presbyterian Church</a> in downtown Hamilton in a <a href="http://www.doorsopenhamilton.ca/" target="_blank">Doors Open 2012</a> event. This church has a splendid Casavant Fr\'e8res organ, which the organist was playing when we arrived. St. Paul\'92s is a beautiful Victorian church, built in 1857, that has wonderful stained glass windows and wood carvings. Like most other churches of its type, it appears to suffer from a declining congregation despite its outstanding architectural attractions. \
What we thought was especially entertaining in this visit was that they allowed Doors Open visitors to sound the bells of St. Paul\'92s bell tower using their mechanical controller levers, which are located in a console up in the bell tower. These levers were marked with musical note names and numbers. A carillonneur could consult a musical score that showed these notes and numbers. It wasn\'92t that difficult to get the hang of the system after a few minutes. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl231\sa230
\cf0 This we thought was a unusually good opportunity for people to play with the bells of an historic church. In fact, I can\'92t think of another time that I have ever encountered such a thing. \
This opportunity the boys took up with gusto and were soon hammering the levers as enthusiastically as they could and attempted to play \'91Mary had a Little Lamb\'92 with eventual success. A church warden looked on sympathetically and tolerantly as two 12 year old boys tried their hardest to create acoustic mayhem using the church bells. The boys were impressed that the outside city could hear the sounds they produced. \
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl231
\cf0 We all thought that this <a href="../2009/10/door-open-smithville/" target="_blank">Doors Open visit</a> was reminiscent of another visit to to another Presbyterian church in the little town of Smithville, where the church tour guides were kind enough to allow the boys to operate their historic hand-pumped organ. This also greatly excited the boys in a similar way.]]></content:encoded> \
\pard\pardeftab720\fi1417\ri0\sl233
\cf0 <excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[This weekend, the boys and I visited St Paul\'92s Presbyterian Church in downtown Hamilton in a Doors Open 2012 event. What we thought was especially entertaining in this visit was that they allowed Doors Open visitors to sound the bells of St. Paul\'92s bell tower using their mechanical controller levers, which are located in a console up in the bell tower. ]]></excerpt:encoded> \
